AHvxFIKtom5sQyXfQ7I1JHOcbGs2Tx6CJf_136KlaCmzm7zRrPJX_CJC4RWIPyBMB4iMNJbIKdcct6wbXXclZEtnW1_M5347qS20PhZhawm_ZuUrqkPZ8VvwpYzaWyu1sSKU7EFVOwf1x1gVfTbdE=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating serialization in Native**\\n\\nI think we need to improve the robustness of our tests in the Native environment, especially since deserialization currently fails due to the missing reflection on the `java.lang.Object` constructor. The developer insists that tests should still execute in Native, but we shouldn't add unnecessary metadata. We’re facing issues because object deserialization seems to require serialization metadata that may not be available. The previous result indicated a `MissingReflectionRegistrationError`, likely due to this lack of metadata. So, how do we make our tests pass under these conditions?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring BigInteger serialization**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether there could be byte arrays in BigInteger. I know that BigInteger is serializable, but in the default readObject method, it only deals with the algorithm string and boolean. It seems like BCDSTU's readObject handles encoded byte arrays. But then I wonder if SubjectPublicKeyInfo might contain byte[] objects that aren't addressed until after the readObject method is invoked. It feels like there's more to untangle here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating public API considerations**\\n\\nI’m reflecting on the user's mention of a normal public API in relation to the BCDSTU public constructor. It seems like this could be acceptable within the provider class. However, I'm wondering if the coverage harness views what's considered \\\"public API\\\" differently for the library. If I were to include provider-based generation, it could potentially trigger the class dynamically, even though it's currently inactive. There's a lot to unpack here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_6B8fDZcZkxoAoyLCoRNlSVMz|fc_08844ab6c18e02d